	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Even if your goal isn't to make your own game, grabbing a NES programming tutorial or two and working through them can really get you up to speed on the basics of how the NES works and how the CPU talks to the other parts.  You'll learn how to find the RESET code, how to read joypads, how to communicate with the Audio Processing Unit (APU) and Picture Processing Unit (PPU)).  Then once you have the basics down you can start tracing through code in your favorite games and you'll recognize stuff like "aha, they are reading the joypads here" or "aha, STA $2007.  They are doing something with graphics here".
<br />
<br />romhacking.net is also a place you should check out.  Read their newbie text documents and you can learn lots of tricks on how to find data (text, palettes, graphics data, etc) in the ROMs.  Knowing where stuff is located in the ROM can help you set up the right breakpoints in your emulator/debugger, so you can know what code you want to be looking at.
<br />
<br />edit: and as you're learning this stuff, ask any questions you have here on the newbie forum.  I found the folks here to be extremely patient and helpful when I was first starting out.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


