	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Dastari wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The first game that I want to take a look at is the original Super Mario Bros. I know it's been done a gazillion times before but that's why I want to look at it.</div>
<br />
<br />Though SMB1 is a fairly simple/small game, and it has been disassembled a lot, I don't know if this would be the best place to start. I'm pretty sure all of the code is hyper-optimized, so it may not be easy to comprehend without studying it really hard.
<br />
<br />If you're looking into hacking existing ROMs, you first want to start out knowing how to communicate with the NES. To do this, you should make some moving sprite demos, scrolling demos, audio demos, etc. NESTech by Y0shi is a great reference for what writes to all the registers do. It covers pretty much all the PPU stuff you'd have to know to work with a game like SMB1. Brad Taylor's sound documentation is pretty much the one that taught me everything (after reading it over and over and over and experimenting, however). I'm pretty sure since the time I read this, other sound documents have been released, but I'm not so sure.
<br />
<br />And of course, you'll want to learn 6502. Many people are overwhelmed when trying to learn this language, probably because they don't learn it in a sort of most important to least important manner. Google GBAGuy's NES tutorials. If you can't find them, I think I have them somewhere. Many people say these tutorials are just plain bad, and it's partially true, but really not in another sense. The part where they are bad is in their accuracy of information. Lots of the example code is sloppy and unreliable, and some of the information the author claims to "not know if it's true or not". But really, these tutorials gave me such a boost into NESDev. They teach you some fundamental stuff about 6502 and about the NES as well. So you should take a look at them, but know that the information could be inaccurate (it's usually slightly inaccurate; it's rarely like completely false, made up crap).
<br />
<br />Also, some good (maybe a bit technical) 6502 resources:
<br />
